<TEXT>
cape town south africas oldest 
city wants to be the countrys first completely desegregated 
municipality 
we are striving toward prize no 1 that the whole city is a 
free settlement area but the government is hardly likely to do 
that said mayor peter muller he meant the national government 
national apartheid laws allow municipalities to decide whether to 
open public amenities such as parks beaches and buses cape town is 
the only major city with no segregated public facilities 
but the national government holds the power to segregate 
residential areas schools and hospitals 
the cape town city council has petitioned repeatedly for the 
right to declare its whole area or sections of it open to free 
settlement the law prohibited multiracial neighborhoods although 
parts of cape town and other cities are mixed with nonwhites 
living illegally in designated white areas 
on march 2 a new law took effect that will allow multiracial 
neighborhoods on a limited basis muller believes that a section of 
cape town will be the first area where all races can live together 
legally since the governing national party legislated residential 
segregation in 1950 
its common cause that district six will be the first free 
settlement area said muller he referred to a hillside near the 
center of town where a squalid but lively multiracial neighborhood 
was bulldozed in the 1960s and declared whites only 
district six is now bordered by allwhite apartment blocks and a 
white technical school but grasscovered lots intersected by empty 
streets and dotted with mosques and churches lie vacant because 
most capetonians felt the demolition had stigmatized the area 
nobody with any kind of sensitivity would have taken it upon 
themselves to in any way develop district six said muller 
before cities were granted the right to open public amenities to 
all races the cape town city council refused to enforce the 
separate amenities act instead of signs demarcating swimming pools 
and toilets for whites or nonwhites muller said the 
council put up notices warning disallowed people that they could 
be prosecuted if they broke the law 
but we didnt prosecute he said 
right through the 1960s we fought the removal of the colored 
mixedrace people from the voters roll and as representatives on 
the council recalled the city councils executive committee 
chairman dick friedlander he was mayor in 1972 when national law 
forced the city council to become allwhite 
we held protest meetings we passed resolutions we did all we 
could friedlander said six of the 34 councilors were 
legislated out of office 
some of the colored councilors were elected from predominantly 
white areas and viceversa muller said we had gotten away 
from racial stigma 
the people of mixedrace indonesian malaysian or indian 
ancestry whose religions customs language and architecture 
contributed to cape towns historic and cultural attraction now have 
no direct voice in how the city is run they can elect neighborhood 
management committees which appoint delegates to a regional council 
south africas parliament sits in cape town the legislative 
capital the first whites to settle in south africa were merchants 
from the dutch east india company who established a trading post in 
cape town in 1652 
the 1985 census put the population of greater cape town 
including suburbs at 154 million 433000 whites 839000 
coloreds 18000 asiatics and 254000 blacks city spokesman ted 
doman said the blacks are grossly undercounted 
officially no blacks live in cape town the adjacent townships 
of langa nyanga and crossroads were taken from the city councils 
control although the city provides most of the water sewerage and 
fire protection services that exist in those areas 
we feel a moral if not a strategic obligation to make sure 
those places have the highest quality of life they can expect 
bearing in mind the shanty type of existence there said muller 
</TEXT>
