<TEXT>
greenpeace protesters today dumped 
outside the us embassy seven barrels of chemical waste they 
claimed was collected from outfall pipes at an american base in 
antarctica 
peter wilkinson a spokesman for the environmental group said 
the waste showed high levels of heavy metals such as cadmium and 
that the protest was part of a stepped up campaign for a cleanup of 
the mcmurdo base 
embassy spokesman mike gould dismissed claims that the contents 
were toxic saying the liquid was nothing more than normal organic 
sewage 
he said the delivery of the drums was nothing but public 
posturing 
the americans are causing a lot of environmental problems in 
antarctica wilkinson said they have one of the worst records 
they must have a sense of responsibility and we are going to make an 
example out of them 
lined up in front of the embassy gate the barrels read danger 
cadmium 
wilkinson said the waste was collected during the groups recent 
expedition to antarctica he accused the united states of gross 
neglect of the fragile environment there saying greenpeace had 
detected chromium lead and copper in wastes dumped into the ocean 
from mcmurdo 
he said the level of cadmium was far in excess of that permitted 
in europe or the united states 
the embassy called in local authorities to remove the barrels 
after greenpeace refused to take them away 
gould said greenpeace had failed to acknowledge that the 
washingtonbased national science foundation which oversees us 
activities in antarctica was committed to cleaning up mcmurdo 
mcmurdo the largest station in antarctica was set up in 1957 
several hundred people work there during the southern hemisphere 
summer 
</TEXT>
