<TEXT>
a federal jury found two transit authority police 
officers guilty tuesday of falsely arresting eight subway riders on 
trumpedup charges 
officers alphonse iannacone 42 an 18year veteran of the 
transit department and mary mcdermott 32 a transit police officer 
since 1980 were each charged with seven counts of conspiring to 
violate civil rights and one count of deprivation of civil rights 
the jury convicted them on all counts after deliberating for 
three days 
the officers face up to 71 years in prison each and stiff fines 
when they are sentenced may 10 by us district judge shirley wohl 
kram 
prosecutors called more than 20 witnesses including the eight 
men arrested by iannacone and mcdermott in 1983 and 1984 and the 
eight victims of those men 
the men all of whom were black hispanic or asian testified 
they were taken off subway trains handcuffed and detained on 
charges of either sexual abuse or attempted grand larceny 
the alleged victims seven women and one man described their 
shock at learning they were listed as the complainants in the cases 
none had sought police assistance the man said he was not a 
pickpocket victim and the women said nothing was missing from the 
purses and they had not felt anyone touching them in a lewd way 
relatives of the two officers shouted oh no and how could 
they do this as the verdict was announced ms mcdermott appeared 
to have tears in her eyes and iannacone appeared shaken 
its really hard for a police officer to get a fair trial 
said defense attorney barry agulnick he and the other defense 
lawyer kenneth kaplan said they would appeal 
transit police chief vincent del castillo issued a statement 
saying while we can never be pleased by the conviction of any 
police officers we are pleased that this old and lingering issue 
has finally been resolved 
the defense had two witnesses a lieutenant who once taught at 
the transit academy explained that discrepancies between arresting 
officers notes and those of the prosecutor are not unusual and a 
psychologist testified that victims of sex abuse often deny it 
occurred 
</TEXT>
