<DOCNO> AP890315-0024 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
moslem anger over the satanic verses a novel 
they say insults their faith has renewed debate over britains 
ancient rarely used blasphemy law 
the law which has been cited in court just twice in the past 67 
years applies only to the christian state church of england 
its failure to embrace other religions was among the reasons the 
law commission an independent panel of academics and jurists 
called in 1985 for its abolition 
but others including moslems are fighting to extend the law to 
other religions to reflect britains multiethnic society 
moslems say it would give them legal ground for opposing salman 
rushdie the author of the satanic verses without resorting to 
the violence urged by iranian leaders who have called for his death 
eight moslem lawyers failed monday to persuade a london 
magistrate to summon rushdie to court on charges of blasphemous and 
seditious libel but they vowed to press their cause 
what we are asking is that the law should be changed so that it 
gives equal status to all citizens said liaqat hussain 
secretarygeneral of the bradfordbased council for mosques 
moslems say the satanic verses blasphemes islam by 
associating the prophet mohammed with prostitutes and suggesting 
that the koran islams holy book was mohammeds invention not 
allahs work 
rushdie born to a moslem family in india is a british citizen 
he has been in hiding in england since feb 14 when iranian leader 
ayatollah ruhollah khomeini ordered moslems to kill him 
the british government has refused to review the blasphemy law 
there is no general consensus for reform says the home office 
john vincent a bristol university history professor wrote in 
the times of london that the governments position looks narrowly 
ethnocentric 
cases of blasphemy and its written form blasphemous libel date 
to the time when church and state were indivisible and an attack on 
christianity was regarded as subversion but church power waned and 
the law came under secular court jurisdiction in 1676 
as part of the system of common rather than statute law offenses 
are decided by legal precedent and punishments are set by the 
courts judges have wide discretion since there is no definition 
for blasphemy 
blasphemy is generally considered as the use of scurrilous 
abusive vilifying ludicrous or offensive words about god or 
christ the christian religion the bible or the formularies of 
the church of england as by law established material must be 
deemed strongly offensive to break the law 
other european nations also have such laws especially the 
strongly roman catholic ones including ireland italy spain and 
portugal says nicholas walter an expert on blasphemy but they 
are not often used he says 
hollands law bans blasphemy that is deliberately intended to 
offend religious feelings but the justice ministry has decided 
rushdies book did not break it 
in france which has no blasphemy law activists have tried to 
ban material on grounds of defamation 
in the first british prosecution for blasphemy since 1922 
antipornography activist mary whitehouse sued gay news magazine in 
1977 for publishing an explicit poem about a roman soldiers 
homosexual fantasies over christs crucified body the magazine and 
editor denis lemon were fined 2500 and lemon drew a ninemonth 
suspended sentence he lost an appeal 
in september state attorneys rejected mrs whitehouses demand 
to prosecute the makers of the film the last temptation of 
christ for showing christ dreaming of having sex with a prostitute 
in its 32 decision in favor of abolishing the law the law 
commission held that it was wrong to single out one religion for 
protection when members of society have a multiplicity of faiths 
or none at all 
the commission noted that most of the public comment it received 
during its fouryear inquiry from 2000 individuals or groups and 
11000 petition signatories supported retaining the law in some 
form but it said none of the proposed substitutes would work 
archbishop of canterbury robert runcie spiritual head of the 
church of england approves of extending the law to all religions 
an option jewish and moslem groups support 
opponents say such a change would have to give protection for any 
organization calling itself a religion including cults and would 
infringe upon freedom of speech 
supporters of an extended law see no threat to free speech 
vincent argues that it is not denials or criticism of religion that 
are blasphemous but truly offensive sometimes inflammatory 
language 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890315-0025 </DOCNO>
