uspanamanian relations have deteriorated since 1987 gen 
manuel noriega the countrys strongman is under indictment in 
florida for drug trafficking 
in recent months the number of official us personnel from 
various government agencies has been scaled back 
lehman told baker of an incident earlier this month when 
panamanian police who are part of noriegas defense forces stopped 
nine buses carrying about 100 american school children the police 
who stopped the buses for about three hours complained the vehicles 
did not have proper license plates 
lehman also cited other incidents of harassment directed against 
panamanians who work at the canal such as with car licenses 
lehman asked if the administration has a fallback position or 
policy in case chaos breaks out 
baker replied that the administration will take whatever steps 
necessary to protect us citizens and the canal but added that 
uspanamanian relations will not be normalized until noriega is 
removed from power 
asked if the administration was considering removing dependents 
from the area baker replied thats being looked into 
noting that elections are set in panama for in may baker 
commented that noriega is unpopular with many panamanians 
i think that there is some reasonable chance that if a 
semifair election is held that the opposition could win the 
election baker said adding but if he steals that 
election hell be even more unpopular 
the united states does not recognize the legitimacy of the 
panamanian government it continues to recognize as the legitimate 
authority ousted president eric arturo delvalle who was deposed 
last february in a coup led by followers of defense chief manuel 
antonio noriega 
the united states has about 1000 military personnel in panama to 
defend the panama canal of the about 8000 employees who work at 
the canal the overwhelming majority are panamanian 
