a proposal for more upfront payments to close 
insolvent savings and loans is gaining support among some democrats 
as an alternative to president bushs bailout plan for the industry 
the general accounting office was asked tuesday by sen don 
riegle chairman of the senate banking committee to work up 
estimates on the impact of absorbing most of the bailout costs 
immediately rather than spreading them over 30 years as bush would 
do 
we may find ourselves a way to save an awfully lot of money 
riegle said after congressional auditors testified it would have 
been cheaper to close and pay off depositors in 179 failed sampls in 
1988 that instead were merged and kept open through government 
subsidies 
comptroller general charles a bowsher said he could not estimate 
how much cheaper outright closings would have been but because many 
of the mergers arranged by the federal home loan bank board carry 
10year aid packages that include tax breaks and guarantees against 
losses for the new owners he estimated the mergers plus expenses in 
closing 43 other sampls last year will total more than 62 billion 
over a decade 
bush would pay for closing or merging another 350 sampls at or near 
insolvency through 50 billion to be raised over the next three 
years from the sale of taxpayerguaranteed bonds by a new offbudget 
government corporation 
the bonds would not be paid off for 30 years and only the annual 
interest costs associated with them would be reflected in the 
federal budget but those interest costs would be 100 million to 
200 million more annually or 3 billion to 6 billion more over 
30 years than if the tab for the bailout were simply lumped into 
the federal debt 
riegle said dumping as much of the bailout costs as possible into 
the fiscal 1989 budget would be a cleaner approach without 
upsetting a resolve by congress and bush to meet a 100 billion 
deficit target in the fiscal 1990 budget 
both have given up hopes of meeting the 136 billion deficit 
target set in the 1985 grammrudman deficit reduction law for fiscal 
1989 which ends sept 30 the white house now says the 1989 deficit 
will be more like 170 billion 
this may be another way to work with the grammrudman 
restraints and at the same time save the taxpayers an awfully lot of 
money riegle said then we wouldnt be forced to make these 
mergers which are very expensive 
rep charles schumer dny a member of the house banking 
