<TEXT>
the worlds biggest iceberg 
believed to be about the size of hong kong is slowly melting in 
antarctica and appears to pose no threat to shipping a news agency 
reported today 
the iceberg which has been codenamed b9 is the longest ever 
accurately recorded and has travelled a 620mile circle since it 
broke away from the ross ice shelf 18 months ago the new zealand 
press association said 
the agency said scientists had been worried it might block the 
entrance to the us research base at mcmurdo sound where 700 
people live during the southern hemisphere summer 
the iceberg is now about 250 miles east of ross island and 185 
miles from where it broke from the shelf glaciologist harry keys 
told the news agency 
when it first cracked off the shelf it was 95 miles long 22 
miles wide and 1155 feet thick dimensions that almost correspond 
with the size of the british colony of hong kong nzpa said 
it said the the giant chunk of ice has since lost six miles of 
its length the agency gave no other details and keys could not be 
reached for independent comment 
