<TEXT>
in what legal authorities called the nations 
first international telephone plea a federal judge heard a prison 
inmate in canada plead guilty to drug charges 
us district judge dickinson r debevoise sat at the head of a 
conference table in his chambers tuesday as claude tremblay admitted 
participating in a northern new jerseybased drug ring prosecuted in 
1982 
defense attorneys the prosecutor news reporters and the court 
reporter listened to tremblays voice over a loudspeaker 
tremblay spoke from archambault prison near montreal where he is 
serving a sevenyear jail term for an unrelated armed robbery 
debevoise sentenced him to five years probation 
i havent heard of a guilty plea by phone said david 
sellers a spokesman for the federal administrative office of the 
courts in washington 
theres a whole wave a big push to be innovative in a 
technological sense among courts he said a number of state 
courts arraign defendants by phone and in some courts lawyers are 
allowed to file lawsuits by facsimile sellers said 
arguments on pretrial motions or emergency search warrant 
applications are more examples of telephone use by the courts said 
lloyd weinreb a professor at harvard law school 
weinreb said a phone plea is not something im aware of but it 
doesnt strike me as very remarkable 
the longdistance hearing took 1 years to arrange and needed 
approval from the us state and justice departments debevoise and 
canadian authorities said attorneys in the case 
after the initial chuckle everybody said theres nothing that 
says you cant do it said michael v gilberti senior trial 
