<TEXT>
more businesses opened and buses 
operated today but 1 million rio de janerio commuters were stranded 
in the second and final day of a nationwide strike to protest a 
governmentimposed wage freeze 
scattered violence was reported 
the subway operated normally in sao paulo south americas 
biggest city with 10 million people and commuters jammed more than 
1300 privately owned buses on the streets however about 4000 
governmentowned buses were stopped 
prostrike demonstrators tried to stop some of the privately 
owned buses from leaving garages police said 30 buses were damaged 
by rockthrowers wednesday and 23 people were arrested 
among those arrested was a franciscan friar who was carrying a 
slingshot and several marbles apparently to damage buses 
according to jairo pires a spokesman for the sao paulo state 
security department 
in rio privately owned buses started circulating today and more 
banks stores coffee shops department stores and supermarkets 
opened their doors in both cities 
however rios subway and commuter trains remained idle for a 
second day today stranding about 1 million commuters 
the jornal do brasil radio station reported three bus passengers 
today opened fire and wounded two pickets who tried to stop the bus 
on rios poor north side 
the strike is clearly petering out and everything indicates a 
majority of the states factory workers will be at their jobs 
said luis carlos granadero a spokesman for the federation of 
industries in sao paulo state 
sergio dos santos of the national strike command acknowledged the 
strike was not attracting support in sao paulo but we hope to 
reverse this trend he said the strike command still did not have 
information on the strike elsewhere in the country 
the twoday strike was organized by brazils two largest labor 
movements the radical left central workers union and the more 
moderate general workers central which claim to represent 35 
million of brazils 60 million workers 
president jose sarneys spokesman carlso henrique de almeida 
santos told reporters in the capital of brasilia that the strike 
caused isolated work stoppages wednesday in many cities but in 
no way can it be considered a general strike 
on wednesday international and domestic airlines flew on normal 
schedules supermarkets gas stations small shops across latin 
americas largest country also opened their doors 
the strike was called to protest the wage freeze that formed part 
of the governments jan 15 austerity plan the economic package cut 
government spending and froze prices to control 1000 percent 
inflation 
the plan brought inflation down from 287 percent a month in 
december to 36 percent for the first 11 days of february the 
latest period for which the government has figures 
jair meneguelli president the central workers union said the 
wage freeze had slashed workers purchasing power by up to 49 percent 
more than half of brazilian workers earn less than 50 a week 
