pan am warned passengers of a bomb threat received 
prior to a transatlantic flight this week unlike in december when 
the threat to flight 103 was disclosed only to the government a 
newspaper reported today 
however the airline did not notify passengers until 15 minutes 
after the delayed flights scheduled departure time leading to 
complaints the boston globe reported 
pan am knew about it and did nothing to forewarn passengers and 
give them an option until the last minute passenger marilyn 
harding told the newspaper in a telephone interview from paris 
she was one of about 17 passengers who changed travel 
arrangements after the airline announced an anonymous telephone 
caller claimed a bomb would be put on the flight monday from new 
york to tel aviv via paris the newspaper said 
most of the flights 200 passengers apparently felt confident 
that their plane would not meet the same fate as pan am flight 103 
which exploded over lockerbie scotland dec 21 killing all 259 
passengers and 11 people on the ground 
i left harding said who wants to spend eight hours up 
there just wondering i think those people took a real gamble 
pan am spokesman alan loflin said that the aircraft passengers 
and their baggage all were carefully screened and that officials 
were satisfied all appropriate measures had been taken when the 
plane took off 
loflin told the associated press today he did not know whether 
any airline ever had similarly notified passengers of a bomb threat 
the flight arrived at its destination without incident 
sen alfonse damato rny on tuesday proposed legislation 
