about 41 percent of the long form 1040 returns filed through last 
weekend had itemized deductions compared with 49 percent for the 
same period last year 
this suggests people may be finding it more advantageous not to 
itemize because of a higher standard deduction and fewer itemized 
deductions permitted under the new tax law said irs spokesman steve 
pyrek 
overall 433 million couples and individuals had filed their 
returns through last week 22 percent more than the 424 million 
last year the irs has processed 293 million also 22 percent more 
than the 287 million at this time in 1988 
the long form has accounted for 211 million returns this year 
or 49 percent of the total compared with 217 million or 51 
percent a year ago filings of the short form 1040a are up 75 
percent to 107 million and use of the singlepage 1040ez for 
single people is up 67 percent to 114 million 
the number of refunds is down 3 percent to 184 million the 
average refund is up 3 percent to 827 
the irs said 861916 taxpayers had filed returns electronically 
through professional return preparers that compares with 362000 in 
the same period a year ago 
