<TEXT>
the economy grew at a moderately strong pace 
early this year with widespread evidence of upward pressure on 
production costs and prices the federal reserve board reported 
wednesday 
consumer spending except for autos has apparently gained 
momentum while manufacturing especially for export continues to 
show strength almost everywhere said the report based on surveys 
conducted by the feds 12 district banks 
the study found that with labor markets tight and factories 
continuing to operate at high levels even as they expand and 
modernize materials and product prices are edging up albeit 
sporadically and at an uneven pace 
the survey known as the tan book was prepared for the march 28 
meeting of the feds policymaking open market committee the panel 
which sets policy for the central bank 
the fed since last march has been nudging interest rates upward 
in an effort to restrain economic growth and thus restrain 
inflation those efforts intensified last month after concern about 
inflation heightened with news that consumer prices rose 06 percent 
in january and wholesale prices surged 1 percent 
the most recent fed report based on survey results received 
through march 8 found that economic activity for most of the 
country is reported to be expanding at a moderately strong pace 
the weakest sectors of the economy are energy and to a lesser 
extent construction it said 
the survey found strong gains in consumer spending with the 
exception of autos for which business has been slow so far this 
year domestic automakers recently boosted incentive offers in an 
effort to stimulate sales and general motors corp has temporarily 
halted production at two plants to reduce inventories 
sales of apparel particularly womens clothing contributed 
significantly to the strength in consumer spending some districts 
also reported brisk sales of home furnishings and electronics 
most of the districts found some tightness in manufacturing labor 
markets with some expectations of increasing upward pressure on 
costs and prices due either to current strong conditions or 
attempts to pass through last years large increases in costs for 
raw materials 
manufacturers generally are optimistic about production prospects 
as exports outpace growth in domestic demand the report said 
the banks reported some of the largest and broadbased increases 
in capital spending often viewed as a barometer of business 
investment plans were in the chicago region in general though 
capital spending is not expected to exceed last years strong pace 
the report said 
often investment spending was aimed at improving efficiency and 
modernizing equipment rather than for expanding capacity the survey 
found 
while industries in several districts are said to be operating 
close to full capacity there are few comments about serious 
bottlenecks the survey said 
</TEXT>
