a famine in northeast mozambique has 
killed almost 5000 people this year and tens of thousands are 
suffering from acute food shortages made worse by a guerrilla war 
the national news agency aim reported wednesday 
catholic missionaries told aim the deaths occurred in memba a 
coastal region about 240 miles south of the border with tanzania 
aim quoted the missionaries as saying tuesday that the toll now 
stood at 4810 
threefourths of the 184000 people in memba face serious food 
shortages according to a representative of radio mozamique in 
northern nampula city 
some of the hardest hit areas are only 30 miles from the busy 
port city of nacala which has an adequate food supply aim reported 
poor transportation and communications systems hampered relief 
operations many people in memba have survived on wild roots and 
fruit since august but the government relief agency did not know 
how bad things were until this year aim reported 
in the past week relief workers have been trying to transport 60 
tons of food to the town of memba each day by road and by boat 
however once the food reaches memba there is no guarantee it will 
make it to those in need because of poor or nonexistent roads aim 
said it said local relief organizations are trying to get 
helicopters to supply some of the more remote villages 
the news agency also said people are moving south to flee 
mozambiques civil war it noted that a widespread migration could 
mean that few crops will be planted this year and the famine could 
get worse 
the 12yearold war pits the marxist government against rebels of 
the mozambique national resistance who have seriously disrupted the 
countrys economy with hitandrun attacks on military and civilian 
targets 
