<TEXT>
the united states and other donor governments 
have settled a threeyear quarrel with latin american nations and 
now are ready to make another 225 billion available to support 
loans in the western hemisphere over the next four years sources 
said wednesday 
agreement was expected to be announced at a meeting of the 
interamerican development bank in amsterdam next week the loans 
would be made through the bank which is owned by 44 countries 
the us treasury which is in charge of the negotiations had no 
comment on the reports a state department official said 
negotiations were still going on 
the reports came after treasury secretary nicholas brady issued a 
proposal last friday for reducing debts to commercial banks to 
which latin american countries owe more than 400 billion 
the sources who spoke on condition they not be named said the 
united states had failed in an attempt to get the right to delay a 
loan for as long as two years a delay which would amount to a veto 
present rules in the interamerican development bank require only 
a 50 percent vote to approve a loan the united states cannot stop 
most loans since it usually has less than 35 percent of the voting 
power 
in 1987 james a baker iii then treasury secretary said the 
bank needed more money but that he wanted to be sure it was well 
used 
the united states is willing to work to secure this funding 
but only if the appropriate checks and balances are adopted and lead 
to improvements in lending quality he told delegates to a meeting 
in miami 
baker is now secretary of state bank president antonio ortiz 
mena a mexican who opposed the changes baker sought has given way 
to enrique v iglesias of uruguay a former highlevel treasury 
official james w conrow has become his deputy 
under the new arrangement a 12month delay would require 40 
percent of the votes on the banks board of directors the sources 
said the united states has 3457 percent of the vote and it counts 
on support from canada which has 438 percent of the vote but 
their 3895 percent total falls just short of the 40 percent hurdle 
in accordance with its voting power the united states would make 
the largest contribution about 78 billion one source said that 
if past arrangements are followed only 45 percent of that about 
350 million actually would have to be paid out over the fouryear 
period the rest of the us contribution and those of other donors 
would only be on call if needed 
in the past such calls have not been made but the assurance that 
they could be enables the bank to borrow cheaply on world markets 
and make its own loans to the american republics on easier terms 
than commercial banks would give 
the interamerican development bank which has its headquarters 
in washington has been lending over 2 billion a year for projects 
to raise living standards most money goes for farm projects with 
large amounts for energy and transport 
since 1961 the largest sums have gone to brazil the third 
worlds largest debtor followed by mexico and argentina of the 17 
donor countries canada is the second largest contributor followed 
by japan and west germany 
