<TEXT>
cleanup of contamination and radioactive waste 
at the governments 12state nuclear weapons complex may cost much 
less than the 60 billion to 100 billion commonly estimated energy 
secretary james d watkins told congress wednesday 
i believe we can do this for a lot less watkins told a 
senate budget subcommittee in his first appearance on capitol hill 
since his swearing in last week 
watkins did not make his own estimate but promised to produce 
later this year a detailed blueprint including cost projections 
for an initial fiveyear effort to clean up the weapons sites and 
modernize the aging facilities 
on a related topic watkins disclosed he is seeking to persuade 
the federal aviation administration to reestablish limits on 
airplane flights over the savannah river plant nuclear facility near 
aiken sc which includes three nuclear reactors that produce 
material used in atomic warheads only a voluntary restriction has 
existed since 1976 when aviation authorities ended tighter limits 
weve got to take a look all around the nuclear weapons 
complex for ways of limiting the threat of an air attack watkins 
said 
the energy department in an estimate published before watkins 
took over said modernization and cleanup of the weapons complex 
would cost at leaset 81 billion over the next 21 years the general 
accounting office has put the cost at over 100 billion 
in testimony before the senate panel keith o fultz the gaos 
director of energy issues said current cost estimates probably were 
too low given that no one yet knows how bad some of the 
contamination is and the feasibility of cleanup 
watkins refuted this he said scenarios for accomplishing the 
cleanup often contained gold watches or frills that are too 
expensive and not needed 
watkins also said he was confident his department could safely 
restart the savannah river plant nuclear reactors in south carolina 
which are the nations only source of tritium a radioactive gas 
needed in the manufacture of nuclear warheads the three reactors 
have been closed for nearly a year because of safety concerns 
i believe we can get those reactors up he said adding that 
he planned to meet soon with senior executives of westinghouse 
electric corp which on april 1 takes over for ei du pont de 
nemours amp co as contract manager at savannah river 
the energy department and westinghouse have said they would 
produce a detailed plan for restarting the savannah river reactors 
by the end of this month 
the timing of a restart at savannah river is considered important 
because the shutdown of production there has raised questions about 
the adequacy of us tritium supplies 
watkins said he already was developing a plan that would get the 
savannah river reactors running again and keep them in safe 
operation for at least a decade time enough to allow for the 
construction of a new generation of reactors 
he defended the bush administrations plan for spending 68 
billion to build two new tritiumproducing reactors one at savannah 
river and the other in idaho critics have said only one and 
possible none will be needed in the foreseeable future 
robert b barker the pentagons assistant secretary for atomic 
energy told the panel the two new reactors would be capable of 
producing 150 percent of the nations tritium needs he strongly 
defended the plan saying extra production capacity was needed to 
guard against unforeseen technical or other problems 
watkins rejected suggestions from some public interest groups 
that postponing or cancelling the new reactor projects could serve 
as a basis for negotiating us and soviet limits on production of 
nuclear materials including plutonium 
we arent yet at a point in arms control where we can throw 
away our bargaining chips he said while acknowledging that 
future arms control agreements could leave the united states with 
excess capacity for nuclear materials 
we may have to eat some of the dollars were putting into 
these he said 
he likened the reactor issue to the development and production of 
pershing 2 and groundlaunched tomahawk cruise missiles that cost 
the united states about 10 billion those missiles are now being 
destroyed under terms of the intermediaterange nuclear forces 
treaty although many never were deployed in the field 
