<TEXT>
president mikhail s gorbachev said wednesday that 
all soviet farmers should be permitted to lease their land and 
decide what to plant in a new national program to ease chronic food 
shortages but he said it will be years before the country can feed 
itself 
gorbachev called food shortages our societys biggest wound 
meat sugar and many other foodstuffs must be rationed in numerous 
soviet regions 
in a tacit acknowledgement that one of his earlier attempts to 
rejuvenate soviet agriculture had failed gorbachev proposed 
abolishing a government superagency created in 1985 to oversee the 
countrys farm sector 
the communist partys policymaking central committee convened 
by party general secretary gorbachev began a twoday meeting 
wednesday largely devoted to agricultural reform it will look for 
ways to increase the food supply and improve traditionally dreary 
rural life 
gorbachev asked the committee to approve an agrarian policy 
that will be able to restore the peasant as the master on the land 
and dependably solve the food problem 
further delay in this matter is simply inadmissible he said 
the 58yearold kremlin leader the former party overseer for 
agriculture and the son of a southern russian peasant said 
conditions in some rural regions were at a critical level with 
mass migration of their populations to cities 
he said farm productivity is so low the soviet union must go 
abroad to buy large quantities of grain meat fruits vegetables 
sugar vegetable oil and some other staples to meet demand at home 
losses of grain due to inefficiency total 40 million metric tons 
equal to soviet grain purchases abroad gorbachev said he 
endorsed focusing on making soviet farming and food processing work 
better rather than on increasing the area under cultivation 
in 1988 gross soviet farm output rose only 07 percent and the 
grain harvest was only 195 million metric tons 16 million below the 
annual average achieved in 198687 according to washington 
dcbased planecon inc which studies soviet economic performance 
gorbachev said the ruling politburo would ask the 300member 
central committee for extensive transition to leasing or 
allowing work collectives and individuals to work stateowned 
farmland in exchange for a fee 
western analysts say leasing benefits would be largely annulled 
if moscowbased bureaucrats retain the right to dictate which crops 
should be planted on individual plots and in which quantities but 
gorbachev said leaseholders should be given a virtual free hand 
let us not fix assignments let us not set deadlines 
gorbachev said gorbachev who first proposed leasing last june 
said all units of the farm should work on the lease principle 
he has said leasing guarantees higher production because 
leaseholders can earn more if they work harder rather than getting 
a fixed salary regardless of output as has been traditional on 
soviet state and collective farms 
gorbachev said more flexible prices for crops purchased by 
the state would go into effect next jan 1 and the number of 
products for which prices are fixed by bureaucrats would be reduced 
he reassured soviet consumers prices will stay the same for the 
next two or three years for bread flour cereals meat fish 
eggs milk sugar butter vegetable oils and baby foods despite 
the admitted pressing need for price reform to curtail state 
subsidies 
one proposal calls for abolishment of the state agroindustrial 
committee created in november 1985 eight months after gorbachev 
was named soviet leader 
he said the giant agency would be replaced by a commission of the 
council of ministers or soviet cabinet 
while calling for urgent measures to improve the soviet diet 
gorbachev said a definite end to food shortages could not be 
expected until the middle of next decade 
gorbachevs onehour 45minute speech on agriculture was later 
shown on staterun television 
the central committee earlier moved to formally elect its top 
leaders and other representatives including gorbachev to the 
nations new parliament 
the communist party is one of 30 organizations with the power to 
choose onethird of the 2250 representatives in the new congress of 
peoples deputies 
despite publicity touting this campaign as the soviet unions 
first election with competing candidates the party chose to 
nominate just 100 persons for its 100 seats party members had 
suggested more than 31000 names 
the food problem is likely to produce far more discussion at the 
central committee plenum since the partys conservative agriculture 
chief yegor k ligachev apparently disagrees with gorbachev on a 
solution 
ligachev has said little about gorbachevs call for leasing 
instead emphasizing collective farming the system that has left 
soviets standing in line for meat and vegetables 
gorbachev said wednesday increased investment to modernize 
collective farms was not enough that huge capital investments in 
agriculture in recent years failed to yield equally substantial 
results 
no one however proposed letting farmers own outright the land 
they till or the breakup of the giant collective and state farms 
that have been the backbone of the soviet agricultural system since 
the days of josef v stalin 
gorbachev said such farms can work with the right management 
techniques 
living standards in the soviet countryside are far lower than in 
cities gorbachev said drastic improvements were needed 
tass said the central committee would reconvene thursday to 
discuss gorbachevs report on agriculture 
