president daniel ortega said wednesday 
his leftist government will allow a roman catholic church radio news 
program to resume and will let 10 expelled priests return to 
nicaragua 
we are trying to create a better climate in our country that 
strengthens the tendency towards total and definitive peace that the 
nicaraguan people demand ortega said after meeting with cardinal 
miguel obando y bravo head of the nicaraguan church 
in neighboring honduras president jose azcona hoyo said his 
government was working on a plan to demobilize thousands of 
nicaraguan rebels in camps near the border and he denied reports 
that the united states has asked the government to let them stay 
another year 
honduras is interested in demobilizing the contras because 
their departure from our territory is in the benefit of national 
security he told reporters 
azcona hoyo and the four other central american presidents agreed 
last month to repatriate the rebels or move them to third countries 
nicaragua said it would move up elections scheduled for november 
1990 and take other steps toward greater democracy 
ortega said wednesday that radio catolicas iglesia news 
program shut down by the sandinista government july 11 would be 
allowed to resume immediately 
in addition to the shutdown the leftist government in july 
expelled us ambassador richard melton and seven other us 
diplomats from nicaragua arrested at least 40 people at a major 
opposition demonstration and closed the opposition newspaper la 
prensa for 15 days 
ortega announced the government would allow 10 priests to return 
to nicaragua and would review a list of other priests barred from 
the country to determine whether they could return 
the sandinistas expelled the 10 priests between 1982 and 1985 for 
allegedly plotting against the government 
those priests eligible to return to nicaragua are francisco 
castelli vicente caudeli francisco san martin santiago de anitua 
and luis corrales of spain vicente huerta jose montero and jose 
maria pacheco of costa rica mario fiandri of italy and mario 
madriz of panama 
