<TEXT>
here are excerpts of president mikhail s 
gorbachevs speech wednesday to a communist party central committee 
meeting whose purpose he described as developing an agrarian 
policy that will be able to restore the peasant as the master on the 
land and dependably resolve the food problem 
they were taken from the englishlanguage translation by the 
official news agency tass 
on the overall problem 
further delay in this matter is simply inadmissible 
drastic changes in the countryside are an essential prerequisite 
for the countrys economic and social progress we all remember 
the concern expressed by delegates to the 19th national party 
conference when discussing the food supply situation in the country 
we described this problem as our societys biggest wound 
the state has to buy large quantities of grain meat fruit 
vegetables sugar vegetable oil and some other staples abroad we 
are still behind developed countries big and small in labor 
efficiency yield capacity and livestock productivity and in the 
diversity and quality of foodstuffs the gap is widening rather than 
narrowing the shortage of food creates social tension and generates 
not merely criticism but actual discontent 
huge capital and other investments have been made in agriculture 
in recent years but the inputs have failed to yield equally 
substantial results 
comrades we should work out an agrarian policy that would enable 
us to blunt the sharp edge of the food problem in the immediate 
future and to grow enough farm produce in terms of both amount and 
choice to stabilize food supplies in the 13th fiveyear plan 
199196 
in the 13th fiveyear period it is planned to increase the 
output of foodstuffs by 26 percent to 30 percent while the output 
of farm produce will grow by 16 percent 
on stalins brutal collectivization of agriculture 
in the process of combatting the kulaks violence was inflicted 
upon the huge mass of middlestrata peasants and even poor ones 
millions of peasants together with their families were torn away 
from their land plots and native areas and suffered misfortunes 
often dying in camps and exile 
on leasing 
let us not fix assignments let us not set deadlines the point 
at issue is the transfer of land and other means of production to 
leaseholders their real control over those means 
if the plenum backs the relevant proposals of the politburo the 
presidium of the ussr supreme soviet and the government and we 
adopt corresponding documents this will create legal and economic 
prerequisites for an extensive transition to leasing 
on price reform 
the purposes of economic restructuring cannot be achieved new 
methods of economic management cannot be introduced and a socialist 
market cannot be formed without a price reform purchase prices 
of some kinds of quality products are so low as not to stimulate the 
development and rational distribution of specialized highly 
marketable production 
the documents circulated among you envisage the introduction of 
new purchase prices of farm produce as of jan 1 1990 the 
range of products priced in a centralized way should be reduced 
on banks 
there is a need for radical restructuring of the activity of 
banks particularly of the agroindustrial bank it is necessary to 
ensure that they are really interested in the development of 
production and act as business partners 
on the independence of agricultural enterprises 
agricultural enterprises are really doubly dependent on the one 
hand they are subordinated to higher bodies along the departmental 
line they are also managed in no less perhaps even in a greater 
degree by local party and government bodies starting from the 
district level 
perestroika presupposes a radical change in the system of 
managing the agrarian sector at all levels we proceeded from 
the assumption that no one should interfere in the daytoday 
economic activities of collective and state farms and still less 
with peasant and individual small holdings 
on equipment problems in agriculture 
workers of the agrarian sector rightly complain that the 
machinemakers abusing their monopoly status often foist upon them 
outdated models of expensive machines with low dependability and 
efficiency standards this is ruinous not only for agriculture but 
for the country as a whole 
we produce more tractors than any other country in the world and 
yet complaints about their short supply are common 
machinemakers should be put in such economic conditions that would 
rule out the manufacture of shoddy equipment 
on waste in agriculture 
our losses in grain harvesting and prestorage treatment amount 
to 15 million and even 20 million tons about as much is lost in 
storage and processing in all comrades the losses equal our 
purchases abroad 
due to the sparsity of meat packing plants their low 
technological standards and inefficient use of raw material meat 
losses even according to the lowest estimates add up to around 1 
million tons this despite the acute shortage of foodstuffs such is 
the dimension of the problem 
many problems stem from the methods of economic management 
peoples attitude to work and their poor motivation to achieve 
better end results 
on ecology 
what must be done as a matter of urgency is putting reclaimed 
lands in proper order and taking measures to put land and water to 
more rational use efforts to come to grips with ecological problems 
that have piled up should not be put off either 
we should drastically raise standards and increase accountablity 
when it comes to the production transportation and storage of 
chemicals and especially their application to the soil 
on life in the villages 
the peasant mode of life has lost its attractiveness and 
prestige people above all the young are leaving villages 
the disregard for the needs of villages and the hypertrophied 
urban development brought about great social distortions and 
complicated the normal economic functioning of whole regions 
the rates of house building in villages in the 13th fiveyear 
period must at least be doubled 
villagers justly raise the issue why rural areas have been put on 
short rations and why peasants have been left to struggle with 
their problems alone although the country has vast resources 
</TEXT>
