warm march winds whipped across portions of the northeast on 
wednesday while powerful thunderstoms lashed michigan and parts of 
the appalachians 
winds gusted to 58 mph at buffalo and rochester ny and 
dubois pa and to 61 mph at johnstown pa high wind warnings were 
in effect for central new york and along the champlain valley 
bordering new york and vermont 
the winds were accompanied by balmy temperatures but a cold 
front swept down from canada across the appalachians bringing 
temperatures in the 30s and 40s from the great lakes to the ohio 
valley 
very strong thunderstorms accompanied by some small hail hit 
the mountains of eastern tennessee and western north carolina 
thunderstorms in michigan triggered a fire in a church and pushed 
the rogue river to near flood stage at rockford 
more than 16 inches of wet heavy snow fell at the ki sawyer 
air force base shutting down routine operations at the lake 
superior post in michigans upper peninsula 
however the stormy weather was fairly shortlived 
this is a typical march storm said meteorologist fred keyes 
of the national weather service bureau in ann arbor mich you 
have all sorts of weather and then it moves out as quickly as it 
came it doesnt hang around like a real winter storm does 
in the west snow fell throughout much of the morning over parts 
of central montana snow was occasionally heavy in the great falls 
area with up to 2 inches of snow per hour at times 
rain was scattered across the pacific northwest 
heavier rainfall during the six hours ending at 1 pm est 
included threequarters of an inch at astoria ore and sixtenths 
of an inch at chattanooga tenn 
mild air brought some record high temperatures to the east 
temperatures warmed into the 50s and 60s over much of new england 
the 70s over the midatlantic coastal states and to the 80s over 
portions of the carolinas 
the temperature hit 83 degrees at martinsburg wv 62 in 
binghampton ny 71 in newark nj and 69 in williamsport pa 
some of the dust that was lifted into the air from the central 
high plains on tuesday settled over eastern new mexico and western 
