paul pressler an architect of the fundamentalist ascendancy 
told the rev richard jackson a phoenix moderate that his comments 
were an attack and a slur on my character 
you have no right to be so judgmental of me added pressler 
a houston appeals court judge you owe me an apology 
jackson countered i dont owe you an apology then he 
repeated four times you dont have one jackson who failed 
last year by a hairbreadth to win the presidency of the 148 
millionmember denomination added 
somebody finally needed to stand face to face with you and say 
these things 
the recorded flareup came late last month after a subcommittee 
recommended a fundamentalistpushed project to undercut 
interbaptist representation in washington by setting up a separate 
office 
however the hallway argument ranged over differences dating back 
over the last 10 years about presslers role as strategist for 
gaining fundamentalist predominance by successively winning the 
presidency since 1979 
the presidents appointive power determines trustees of the 
denominations huge network of agencies and institutions on a 
gradual basis and last years presidential outcome marked the shift 
to general fundamentalist control 
that includes a current majority of the central oversight body 
the executive committee which approved the subcommittees 
recommednation voting 4227 to set up the separate washington 
agency 
called the religious liberty committee it would serve as an 
alternative to the baptist joint committee on public affairs a 
longtime religious liberty watchdog for nine baptist bodies in the 
nations capital 
the plan provides that the denomination through its new arm 
would continue relationship with the interbaptist office but 
also run its own activities 
the action remains subject to two successive annual conventions 
the first one this june in las vegas nev 
fundamentalists have steadily criticized the joint agency 
especially for not advocating prayer in public schools nor opposing 
abortion the joint agency contends its mandate prevents involvement 
in the abortion debate 
the rev james m dunn the agencys executive director called 
the move to set up a separate southern baptist office 
shortsighted and divisive 
he said the joint agency has provided a consistent witness to 
religious liberty and will not compromise historic baptist 
convictions for a mess of politically tainted pottage 
this was only one of the issues festering in the denomination 
including status of its educational institutions 
one of them southeastern baptist theological seminary in wake 
forest nc has been found failing to meet accreditation 
standards following resignation of its former administration in 
protest at trustee changes 
a study committee of the southern association of colleges and 
schools said new requirements of belief in biblical inerrancy 
appears to have been arbitrarily imposed and responsibility of 
faculty curtailed 
biblical inerrancy is the yardstick pressed by 
fundamentalists now prevailing among institutional trustees and 
broadly applied through the denominations operations 
although insistence on this literalistic view of the bible 
powered the fundamentalist drive the rev milton ferguson 
president of midwestern baptist theological seminary in kansas city 
observes 
the real issue is no longer the bible but whether or not we 
can and will find ways to reestablish trust among ourselves 
moderates beaten out in the last decade of elections have 
sought mutual reinforcement in new independent organizations such as 
the southern baptist alliance a coalition of about 50 churches 
totalling 40000 
it insists on the soul competence of individuals to interpret 
the bible as they understand it an historic baptist principle 
the denominations past principles are in eclipse kirby 
godsey president of the denominations mercer university in macon 
ga told an alliance meeting last fall 
in the midst of these frightening shadows of denominational 
elipse we huddle together to find reassurance and light enough to 
sustain us he said we are baptists in a denomination that has 
stopped being baptist 
the alliance insists it doesnt presently plan any break from the 
denomination but is planning to help fund a new seminary not 
dominated by fundamentalists 
another unofficial group called baptists committed to the 
southern baptist convention was formed last december saying it 
represents the centrist mainstream of southern baptists 
we support the restoration of our convention not its 
destruction says the rev winfred moore of amarillo texas 
chairman of the group and twice unsuccessful candidate for the 
denominational presidency 
whether moderates will enter a presidential candidate in june 
after nine years of defeats remained uncertain but the 
fundamentalistbacked incumbent the rev jerry vines of 
jacksonville fla says he is open to reelection 
