<DOCNO> AP890315-0295 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the us merchandise trade deficit narrowed 
sharply in january to 949 billion the lowest imbalance in three 
months as a big decline in consumer imports offset a higher oil 
bill the government reported wednesday 
the commerce department said that the imbalance between imports 
and exports fell by 137 percent from a revised december deficit of 
1099 billion as the united states posted a rare trade surplus with 
europe and the deficit with japan fell to its lowest point in 2 
years 
the bush administration hailed the development as an encouraging 
sign of progress in whittling down the countrys huge trade deficit 
but many private economists were far less encouraged 
some analysts called the january figure a onemonth fluke in what 
they believe will be an otherwise dreary outlook for us trade 
prospects this year 
in 1988 the us trade deficit declined by 21 percent to 11976 
billion as a boom in export sales helped provide twofifths of the 
years total economic growth 
but analysts are forecasting that export sales despite 
aggressive marketopening efforts on the part of the administration 
will slow significantly in 1989 while americas foreign oil bill 
increases reflecting rising world oil prices 
the january report is going to be the last reduction we get in 
our trade deficit for quite some time said michael evans head of 
a washington forecating firm our export boom ran out of steam 
some time ago and now we are seeing the effect of higher oil 
prices 
evans predicted that the us trade deficit would actually 
increase to 130 billion this year based on the adverse trends 
that would be a blow to the administration which is counting on 
exportled growth to help keep the us economy moving forward at a 
rapid clip bringing in the government revenues needed to lower the 
federal budget deficit 
both commerce secretary robert mosbacher and us trade 
representative carla hills the administrations top trade 
officials issued statements hailing the january decline as an 
encouraging development 
the year is starting on a plus note mosbacher said our 
aim should be to build on this improvement in the months ahead 
the administration has adopted a tough trade stance pledging to 
work aggressively to open foreign markets to more us products but 
many private economists expressed doubt that there is much room left 
for american exports to grow given the 27 percent jump in export 
sales which occurred last year 
we have to get a decline in imports for us to mount another 
significant improvement in our trade deficit said allen sinai 
chief economist of the boston co sinai said any lasting drop in 
imports was unlikely until there is a significant slowdown in the 
us economy 
the january deficit reflected a surplus of 465 million with 
western europe the first trade surplus there since september 1983 
primarily reflecting higher us sales in britain and france 
the trade deficit with japan dropped to 35 billion with 
twofifths of that decline reflecting a drop in japanese car 
imports the japanese deficit as usual the largest of any country 
fell to its lowest point since a 337 billion imbalance in june 
1986 
william t archey the top trade expert with the us chamber of 
commerce said it remained to be seen whether this decline was just 
a blip in the monthly statistics or reflected the fact that more 
japanese cars are being manufactured at plants in the united states 
starting with the january report the government is removing the 
cost of shipping and insurance from the import totals a bookkeeping 
change that has the effect of lowering each months trade deficit by 
about 15 billion the adjustments were also made to the prior 
months data to conform with the new reporting system 
with shipping and insurance charges included the 1988 
merchandise trade deficit was 1373 billion the measurement change 
removing the costs of shipping and insurance adopted by congress at 
the urging of the reagan administration will return the government 
to the trade accounting procedures used before 1979 
the january deficit of 949 billion reflected declines in both 
imports and exports which had hit alltime record levels in 
december 
us imports fell by 69 percent to 3729 billion as sales of 
foreign consumer goods declined by 14 billion and foreign car 
shipments declined by 700 million 
us imports of oil however were up sharply in january rising 
61 percent to 35 billion reflecting rising prices the price per 
barrel jumped to 1446 from 1310 in december while the number of 
barrels fell to 78 million barrels per day from 811 million 
barrels in december 
analysts said with world oil prices already at 18 per barrel 
americas oil bill would be rising even higher in the future 
us export sales fell 43 percent to 278 billion down from a 
record 2906 billion in december the drop reflected declines in 
sales of capital goods down 12 billion and industrial supplies 
which fell 600 million 
</TEXT>
