<TEXT>
commerce secretary robert mosbacher on 
wednesday said japan must do more to open its markets to us 
hightechnology computer products contending that it has failed to 
live up to a 1986 commitment involving semiconductor sales 
in a speech to a us electronic industries trade association 
mosbacher sounded a tough line with japan the country running the 
largest trade surplus with the united states 
he said american manufacturers of semiconductors and 
supercomputers were selling products that were second to none in the 
world 
but despite this strength these sectors have been unable to 
capture their fair share of world markets mosbacher told the 
electronic industries association our semiconductor industry 
especially has been hurt by unfair pricing practices around the 
world and lack of access to japans market the worlds largest 
market 
mosbacher said he realized that there were many cultural 
reasons behind japans desire to keep its markets closed but 
changes must come as painful as it might prove japan must open its 
semiconductor market to foreign producers 
mosbacher said the japanese were failing to live up to the spirit 
of a pledge they made in september 1986 to raise the foreign 
largely us share of their nations semiconductor market to 
slightly above 20 percent in five years 
at the time the us share of the japanese semiconductor market 
was around 8 percent it is now around 11 percent semiconductors 
are the thin wafers at the heart of computers and other electronic 
devices 
mosbacher has said in the past that japan will be unable to meet 
the 20 percent goal by 1991 unless it dramatically accelerates its 
marketopening efforts he has suggested that a more appropriate 
level of us semiconductor sales would be between 15 percent and 20 
percent by the end of this year 
mosbacher said american producers of supercomputers had only been 
able to capture 6 percent of the university and government market in 
japan in part because of the japanese practice of issuing technical 
specifications which favored japanese suppliers 
the reagan administration imposed higher tariffs on certain 
japanese electronic goods in 1987 because of the semiconductor 
dispute mosbacher said in wednesdays speech that president bush 
would lift those sanctions if japan demonstrated a greater 
commitment to opening the door to us products 
i know that president bush is quite willing to lift the 
sanctions that president reagan imposed mosbacher said but 
japan must give him a reason for doing so he must have continuing 
evidence of a more open market to act 
</TEXT>
